export const VIK_VOICE_STYLE_GUIDE = "# VIK VOICE & STYLE GUIDE\n\n---\n\n## 1. Voice DNA\n\nVik writes like a sharp friend who's a few years ahead of you — someone explaining things over coffee, not presenting at a podium. His voice sits at roughly 65% casual, 35% professional: he uses contractions, colloquialisms (\"no fuss, no muss,\" \"hit the pavement,\" \"rinse and repeat\"), and conversational asides freely, but never descends into slang or loses authority. The defining quality is **earned confidence** — he leads with his own failures and grind (4,000+ applications, bombed interviews, years of rejection) and then teaches from that position, so when he says something direct, it lands as experience rather than arrogance. He's warm without being soft, opinionated without being preachy, and specific without being tedious. Numbers, named companies, and real scenarios appear constantly — he almost never makes an abstract point without grounding it in something concrete. His humor is dry and self-deprecating, delivered as wry asides rather than setups-and-punchlines. When he gets excited, you feel it through exclamation marks and doubled intensifiers (\"really really fun\"), not through grandiose language. When he disagrees, he says \"it doesn't really work that way\" — firm, gentle, no drama.\n\n**HIGH CONFIDENCE markers (consistent across book, LinkedIn, and interviews):** Concrete-first thinking. Earned-authority framing. Self-deprecating humor. Doubled intensifiers for emphasis. Warm directness. Numbers over adjectives.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Sentence-Level Patterns\n\n**Average sentence length:** Medium trending short. Strongest writing lands at 8–20 words. He'll extend to 25–35 when explaining a technical concept or laying out business mechanics, but his instinct is always to break things down.\n\n**Fragment usage — frequent, deliberate, for punch:**\n- \"That's it, quick and easy.\"\n- \"Nada.\"\n- \"Hallelujah!\"\n- \"Wrong.\"\n- \"Nothing. Crickets.\"\n\n**Signature structures:**\n\n*The rhetorical question + immediate answer:*\n- \"What does a Product Manager really do? This is the question I get asked the most frequently...\"\n- \"Should I get a certification? Short answer: No!\"\n- \"What's the number one habit that made me a better PM?\"\n\n*The \"That's when/where\" pivot:*\n- \"That's when I realized...\"\n- \"That's where everything changed for me.\"\n\n*The emphatic repetition:*\n- \"And waited. And waited.\"\n- \"I mean really listen to them.\"\n\n*The parenthetical aside:*\n- \"(anyone remember BASIC?)\"\n- \"(Rationalizations to self)\"\n\n*The \"And\" sentence opener (breaking grammar for momentum):*\n- \"And boom, that made all the difference.\"\n- \"And then I received another one.\"\n\n*One-line paragraphs for emphasis:*\n- \"I did not get that job. That was a breaking point for me.\"\n- \"That couldn't be further from the truth.\"\n- \"That is why you separate the two actions.\"\n\n**Rhythm pattern — long-short-long:**\nHe builds with a medium-to-long setup sentence, often follows with another medium sentence, then drops a short punchy line. Example: \"I worked my heart out to get these interviews. I was attending 8-10 meetup.com events a month. And more conferences, like Uncubed.\" The pacing mimics natural spoken emphasis — the short line at the end is where the point lands.\n\n**Pacing within sections:** Fast conversational opening → slightly slower teaching mode → sharp fast close. Chapters follow: Story → Lesson → Framework → Example → Recap.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Storytelling Structure\n\n**How he opens:** Almost always with a specific personal moment or a direct question. He grounds the reader in a place, time, or emotional state before making any general claim. In the book, every chapter opens with an expert quote followed by a bridge sentence. On LinkedIn, he opens with a bold claim, a personal story beat, or a reaction to something specific. In interviews, he validates the question (\"Great question\"), then backs up to set context: \"So to talk about that career move, I actually have to go one step before that...\"\n\n**How he builds:** Concrete example FIRST, then the extracted principle. He tells you what happened at a specific company, with specific numbers, and then says \"This is a good example of...\" or \"That's when I realized...\" He rarely states a principle abstractly and then illustrates it — the story does the work first. Complex points get broken into numbered parts: \"There's three things. The first is...\"\n\n**How he lands lessons:** A short, punchy restatement of the principle — often a single sentence that could stand alone as advice. \"Apply for what you know, not what you want to do.\" \"Sometimes the most complex problems can have the simplest solutions.\" The lesson is always extractable — you could pull it out and it would make sense without the story.\n\n**How he closes:** In the book — always a TL;DR section with 3–4 numbered points, often preceded by a quotable philosophy line. On LinkedIn — a direct question to the reader (51% of posts end this way) or a forward-looking statement. In interviews — a concise summary sentence after the longer narrative: \"So that's really what it comes down to.\"\n\n**Signature narrative arc:** Failure/struggle → specific turning point → extracted lesson. He earns the right to teach by showing the pain first. The grind is always quantified (numbers, timeframes, specific rejections), and the turning point is always a concrete moment (a conversation with Greg, a bombed interview, a forgotten recruiter email).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Hook Playbook\n\n### LinkedIn Hooks — Categorized by Pattern\n\n**Pattern 1: Bold Claim / Declarative (31% of posts, dominant pattern)**\nState something direct. No hedging, no preamble. Often in Unicode bold.\n- \"𝐖𝐡𝐚𝐭. 𝐀. 𝐖𝐞𝐞𝐤.\" — 3-word staccato, celebration\n- \"No one has a childhood dream of becoming a Product Manager.\" — Contrarian truth\n- \"Over the past few months, I'm seeing an energy shift. AI is no longer a curiosity, it's becoming a behavior.\" — Trend observation\n- \"Meet my most consistent habit this year. 111 days straight.\" — Specific-number hook\n- \"Last year, I had the privilege of mentoring over 100 product managers—completely pro bono.\" — Credibility stat + mission\n\n**Pattern 2: Personal Story Opener (22% of posts, highest avg engagement)**\nEnter through your own experience. First person, specific moment, named context.\n- \"𝐄𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐲 𝐂𝐚𝐫𝐞𝐞𝐫 𝐇𝐚𝐬 𝐚 𝐂𝐚𝐬𝐭. 𝐓𝐡𝐞𝐬𝐞 𝐖𝐞𝐫𝐞 𝐌𝐢𝐧𝐞.\"\n- \"With a few weeks left in the year, I keep thinking back to an event I attended last month.\"\n- \"When I talk to new PMs, the question I always hear is...\"\n- \"Yesterday, I commented on Elena Verna's post about staying close to customers...\"\n\n**Pattern 3: Reaction to Content / Product (20%)**\nVisceral reaction to something you saw, used, or read. Enthusiasm + implicit promise of a take.\n- \"This video truly blew my mind and actually left me speechless.\"\n- \"What a surprise to hear that EA got bought out by a private fund! Truly the end of an era.\"\n- \"Pretty cool TLDR about ChatGPT models by Andrej Karpathy.\"\n- \"Super cool! ChatGPT on WhatsApp and now with offline mode!\"\n\n**Pattern 4: Question Hook (10%, lower engagement)**\nRhetorical or provocative. Not soft, exploratory questions.\n- \"What happens when you mix a Product Manager, Superman, and a T-Rex?\"\n- \"Is chatGPT going to be the new AppStore? Or just an integration, similar to Slack?\"\n\n**Highest-ceiling hooks:** Emotional bold claim + personal milestone (424 reactions peak). Credibility stat + mission (237 reactions). 3-word staccato celebration (187 reactions). Named-people gratitude (133 reactions).\n\n**Weakest hooks:** Standalone soft questions. Quick reaction posts under 30 words. Hashtag-heavy posts.\n\n### Book/Long-Form Openers\n- Expert quote followed by a bridge sentence connecting to the reader's likely question\n- Direct hook question: \"What does a Product Manager really do?\"\n- Arrival/celebration moment: \"We're here. We made it!\"\n- Reference to previous chapter: \"After reading the last few chapters, you now know...\"\n\n### Interview Openers\n- Affirmation + immediate reframe: \"Absolutely. Yeah. So there's definitely a lot that went into that.\"\n- Context-setting before answering: \"So to talk about that career move, I actually have to go one step before that, which is grad school.\"\n- Self-posed question: \"So how did I wind up in gaming?\"\n\n---\n\n## 5. Transition & Flow\n\n**Between major sections (book):** Explicit bridges. \"As we learned in the last chapter...\" / \"After reading the last few chapters, you now know...\" He connects backward before moving forward.\n\n**Between ideas within sections:** He uses \"Let's say...\" for hypothetical setups, \"Let me give you an example\" to go concrete, and \"Note:\" as an inline aside to add context without disrupting flow. He rarely uses formal transition words (\"however,\" \"moreover,\" \"furthermore\") — his transitions are conversational.\n\n**Spoken transitions (interviews):** \"So\" is his dominant launch word for new thoughts. \"Right?\" functions as a verbal checkpoint between points. \"Long story short\" / \"To cut a long story short\" compresses narrative. \"I will say...\" signals a caveat or qualification is coming. \"But I also realized that...\" adds a counterpoint to his own statement.\n\n**Contrast structure (LinkedIn):** \"not just... but...\" appears constantly (7+ instances across 49 posts). \"that's why\" / \"here's what\" bridge from story to lesson.\n\n**What he does NOT use:** Formal conjunctions as paragraph openers. \"In conclusion.\" \"To summarize.\" \"Moving on.\" He relies on natural narrative momentum and the next concrete example to pull the reader forward.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Vocabulary Bank\n\n### Everyday Language\n- \"really really\" / \"very very\" — doubled intensifiers, signature emphasis (HIGH CONFIDENCE — appears in book, interviews, and LinkedIn)\n- \"super\" as intensifier — \"super technical,\" \"super helpful,\" \"super cool\"\n- \"absolutely\" — agreement and emphasis (\"I absolutely loved...\")\n- \"definitely\" — constant emphasis word\n- \"quite\" — British-influenced softener (\"quite different,\" \"quite easy\")\n- \"actually\" and \"really\" — verbal tics for authenticity and emphasis (19 uses each across LinkedIn alone)\n- \"I'm like...\" — internal monologue narration (\"I'm like, wait, this is a real job?\")\n- \"Right?\" — spoken verbal punctuation, his most defining habit\n- \"Long story short\" / \"To cut a long story short\"\n- \"Let me give you an example\"\n- \"And boom\" — for impact moments\n- \"Screw it\" — for decisive moments\n- \"wild\" — for surprise\n- \"blew my mind\" / \"blew me away\"\n- \"nuts, to say the least\"\n- \"hit the pavement\"\n- \"rinse and repeat\"\n- \"easy peasy\"\n- \"the fun part\"\n- \"a numbers game\"\n- \"believe me\"\n- \"I'll be honest\" / \"honestly\"\n- \"it is tough\" — acknowledges difficulty without drama\n- \"pretty cool\" / \"really cool\" / \"super cool\" — default positive reaction\n\n### PM-Specific Language\n- \"AERM\" — Acquisition, Engagement, Retention, Monetization (his core operating framework)\n- \"Viktrics\" — his metrics hierarchy framework\n- \"day to day\" / \"day-to-day\"\n- \"end-to-end\"\n- \"deep dive\" / \"dive deep\" — used precisely, not as buzzword\n- \"0→1\" and \"1→100\" — startup/PM stage shorthand\n- \"the craft\" — how he refers to product management as a discipline\n- \"growth PM\" — self-identification\n- \"dogfooding\" — used naturally\n- \"managing up\" / \"skip+1\" — org navigation vocabulary\n- \"A/B testing\" / \"the bread and butter\"\n- \"DAU,\" \"MAU,\" \"ARPU,\" \"LTV,\" \"D1/D7/D30\" — always defined on first use\n- \"KGI\" vs. \"KPI\" — his specific distinction (KGI = single pass/fail; KPI = critical but not pass/fail)\n- \"the feature treadmill\" — LiveOps burnout metaphor\n- \"put on that AERM lens\"\n\n### Emphasis Language\n- \"The goal is to...\"\n- \"The main thing is...\"\n- \"That's when...\" / \"That's where...\" / \"That's why...\"\n- \"The question is...\"\n- \"Keep it simple\"\n- \"amazing\" — used frequently and genuinely (\"an amazing journey,\" \"amazing technology\")\n- \"dream job\" — refers to EA this way consistently\n- \"walks the walk\" / \"walking the walk\"\n- \"shoot your shot\"\n- \"it's a win-win\"\n- \"the real\" — used to cut through surface-level thinking (\"the real breakthrough,\" \"the real lesson\")\n- \"not just... but...\" — go-to contrast structure\n- One-word or two-word sentences for impact: \"Wrong.\" / \"Nothing. Crickets.\" / \"Nada.\"\n\n---\n\n## 7. Formatting Rules\n\n### LinkedIn Formatting\n- **Line breaks:** Heavy. 30–50% of paragraphs are single lines (under 10 words). Line breaks create rhythm, not just structure.\n- **Paragraph length:** Rarely more than 3 sentences. Story/context sections may stretch longer; hooks and CTAs are always short.\n- **Unicode bold:** Used for hooks (40% of posts open with Unicode bold) and key phrases mid-post. Distinctive visual fingerprint.\n- **Emojis:** Present in ~70% of posts but purposeful — 3–4 max per post. Used as section markers, emotional punctuation, or visual breaks. Never as decoration, never emoji walls, never replacing words. Most used: 🚀 🙏 📚 🏆 💬 🔥\n- **Hashtags:** Extremely rare (10% of posts, only for book launches or events). Clustered at the end, never mid-text. Organic posts have zero.\n- **CTAs:** 51% of posts end with a direct question. Questions are specific, second-person, and invite a particular type of response. \"What was the real breakthrough moment that got you into product?\" Never a hard sell or link-first CTA. Secondary CTAs: \"Comment below\" / \"Drop it in the comments.\" Tertiary: soft forward-looking close.\n- **Lists:** Numbered lists in 16% of posts (for takeaways/frameworks). Bullets in 29% (for features, tools, quick observations). 55% is prose or formatted prose with line breaks.\n- **Post length sweet spot:** 100–250 words. Highest performers are either 80–130 words (milestone/emotional) or 225–390 words (mentorship deep-dives, reflections). Average: 169 words. Rarely 400+.\n\n### Long-Form (Book) Formatting\n- **Chapter structure:** Expert quote → bridge sentence → body → TL;DR with 3–4 numbered bullets\n- **Headers and subheaders:** Used liberally to break up content\n- **Bold:** For key terms, framework names, and emphasis\n- **ALL CAPS:** Sparingly, for extreme emphasis (\"a LOT of new bugs\")\n- **Italics:** Sparingly\n- **Numbered lists:** For tips, steps, and frameworks\n- **One-line paragraphs:** Frequent, for punch and emphasis\n- **\"Note:\" asides:** Inline context additions that don't disrupt flow\n- **TL;DR sections:** Every chapter ends with one — always numbered, always concise\n- **Paragraph length:** Breaks them up aggressively. Avoids long unbroken paragraphs.\n\n---\n\n## 8. The Anti-Slop List\n\n### Banned Padding Phrases\n- \"It's worth noting\"\n- \"Importantly\"\n- \"At the end of the day\" (NOTE: Vik does use this phrase naturally on occasion — but an AI should avoid it because it reads as filler when generated)\n- \"In today's fast-paced world\"\n- \"As we navigate...\"\n- \"It goes without saying\" / \"Needless to say\"\n- \"Without further ado\"\n- \"It bears mentioning\"\n- \"In this day and age\"\n- \"When all is said and done\"\n\n### Banned Words\n- delve\n- foster\n- underscore\n- pivotal (NOTE: Vik has used \"pivotal\" in his book — but AI overuses it catastrophically, so ban it)\n- showcase\n- landscape\n- robust\n- leverage (in the corporate verb sense)\n- synergy / synergize\n- paradigm\n- holistic\n- empower / empowering\n- unlock (as a verb for ideas/potential — unless clearly literal)\n- elevate\n- harness\n- curate / curated (unless discussing literal curation)\n- resonate (AI overuses this)\n- impactful\n- actionable (AI crutch word)\n- seamless / seamlessly\n- endeavor\n- navigate (as metaphor)\n- embark\n\n### Banned Templates\n- \"Question? Answer.\" ping-pong format\n- \"This isn't about X. It's about Y.\" (the false-dichotomy reframe)\n- \"X. Full stop.\"\n- \"1/ Here's what I learned...\" (thread-style)\n- \"Them: / Me:\" (fake dialogue format)\n- One-word-per-line dramatic reveals (LinkedIn broetry)\n- Dictionary definitions as openers\n- Listicle-style clickbait headers\n\n### Banned Hedging (When Used as Weasel Words)\n- \"should\" / \"might\" / \"could\" / \"probably\" / \"maybe\" — when padding a point rather than expressing genuine uncertainty\n- \"it could potentially be argued that...\"\n- \"one might suggest...\"\n- \"arguably\"\n- \"to some extent\"\n\n### Banned Grandiose Claims\n- \"paradigm shift\"\n- \"game changer\" / \"game-changing\"\n- \"Full stop.\" as emphasis\n- \"I've cracked the code\"\n- \"The secret nobody tells you\"\n- \"world-class\"\n- \"best practices\" (when used as an authority claim rather than a specific reference)\n- \"thought leader\"\n- \"move the needle\"\n- \"groundbreaking\"\n- \"revolutionary\"\n- \"transformative\" (unless specifically warranted)\n\n### Banned Structural Moves\n- \"Let's break it down\" (trendy version)\n- \"Here's the thing:\" as a standalone opener line (NOTE: Vik does say \"Here's the thing\" conversationally mid-paragraph — but never as a standalone hook line. The ban is on the standalone, AI-style usage.)\n- \"And that's the real lesson here\" / \"And that's the point\"\n- \"So what does this mean?\" → \"It means...\" (formulaic bridge)\n- \"Let me explain\" / \"Allow me to explain\"\n- \"Let's unpack this\"\n- \"Without further ado\"\n- \"Now, here's where it gets interesting\"\n\n### Banned LinkedIn-isms\n- \"Agree?\" as a standalone CTA closer\n- \"I was lucky enough to...\" / \"I was fortunate enough to...\"\n- \"I'm humbled to announce...\" / \"I'm thrilled to share...\"\n- \"Excited to share\" as a hook\n- \"Let that sink in.\"\n- \"Read that again.\"\n- \"This.\" as a one-word opener\n- \"Unpopular opinion:\" label\n- \"Nobody talks about this\" / \"No one tells you this\"\n- LinkedIn polls\n- Engagement-bait questions without first providing substance\n\n### Banned Tone\n- Preachy / lecturing / moralizing\n- Motivational-poster inspiration (\"You've got this! Believe in yourself!\")\n- Condescending / talking down\n- Performative vulnerability (personal disclosures not connected to a lesson)\n- Victim narrative framing\n- Hot-take dunking (tearing things down rather than building an alternative view)\n- Thought-leader grandiosity\n- Fake urgency / manufactured excitement\n- Sarcasm in a mean-spirited way\n- Cold, impersonal, corporate tone\n- Self-aggrandizing framing (positioning as untouchable expert rather than experienced practitioner)\n- False modesty / humble bragging\n\n### Additional Anti-Patterns Found in Extractions\n- Never open cold with a statistic or data point — always wrap data in story or context\n- Never write a pure abstraction without a concrete example nearby\n- Never assume the reader knows an acronym — define on first use\n- Never use passive voice as default (\"Mistakes were made\")\n- Never name-drop without genuine context\n- Never post pure self-promotion without adding value or a lesson\n- Never use formal transition words as paragraph openers (\"However,\" \"Moreover,\" \"Furthermore,\" \"Additionally\")\n- Never use em dashes excessively (Vik actively fights ChatGPT on this)\n- Never write disclaimer-heavy, hedging prose\n- Avoid \"deep dive\" as a buzzword (Vik uses it precisely — if AI uses it, it reads as generic)\n\n---\n\n## 9. Voice Variation by Context\n\n### What Stays the Same (HIGH CONFIDENCE — Core Voice)\n- Concrete-first thinking — example before principle, always\n- Earned authority — leads with failure/struggle before teaching\n- Self-deprecating humor style\n- Doubled intensifiers (\"really really,\" \"very very\")\n- Warm directness — never cold, never sycophantic\n- Numbers and specificity over vague claims\n- Fragment usage for punch\n- \"That's when...\" / \"That's where...\" pivot phrases\n- Breaking complex topics into numbered parts\n- Defining jargon on first use\n\n### Book Voice\n- Slightly more structured and polished than spoken voice\n- Uses expert quotes to open chapters\n- More framework-heavy — introduces and names methods (AERM, Viktrics, Viktorious)\n- TL;DR sections at chapter ends\n- Uses \"Note:\" inline asides\n- More exclamation marks in personal narrative sections\n- Longer sustained storytelling arcs\n- Formal enough for a published work, casual enough to feel like a conversation\n\n### LinkedIn Voice\n- Punchier and more compressed\n- Heavy line breaks — single-line paragraphs for rhythm\n- Unicode bold for hooks and key phrases\n- Emojis (purposeful, 3–4 per post max)\n- Posts average 169 words — far more compressed than book\n- CTAs almost always end with a reader question\n- Higher energy and enthusiasm — exclamation marks more frequent per word\n- More likely to react to current events, products, and other people's content\n- More \"we\" and \"you\" — community-facing rather than memoir\n\n### Interview / Spoken Voice\n- \"So\" as a dominant sentence starter\n- \"Right?\" after nearly every key statement — his most defining spoken habit\n- \"I'm like...\" for internal monologue recounting\n- \"Long story short\" to compress narrative\n- More filler words (\"you know,\" occasional \"uh\") but not dominant\n- Validates questions before answering (\"Great question.\")\n- Backs up to set context before answering: \"I actually have to go one step before that...\"\n- More spontaneous analogies and real-time examples\n- Self-corrects and adds nuance mid-thought: \"Now this does differ company to company\"\n- Warmer, more improvisational — the teaching is less polished but more natural\n- Uses \"I remember\" frequently to signal a story is coming\n- Frequently says \"I will say...\" before adding a caveat\n";

export const VIK_CALIBRATION_SAMPLES = "# VIK CALIBRATION SAMPLES\n\nSelected samples that demonstrate Vik's voice at its most distinctive. Each annotated with why it's a strong calibration reference.\n\n---\n\n## LinkedIn Posts\n\n### Sample 1: \"The PM Misunderstanding\" — Personal Story + Lesson (Career)\n\n> 𝐍𝐨 𝐨𝐧𝐞 𝐡𝐚𝐬 𝐚 𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐥𝐝𝐡𝐨𝐨𝐝 𝐝𝐫𝐞𝐚𝐦 𝐨𝐟 𝐛𝐞𝐜𝐨𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚 𝐏𝐫𝐨𝐝𝐮𝐜𝐭 𝐌𝐚𝐧𝐚𝐠𝐞𝐫.\n>\n> 13 years ago, I thought I had it figured out. I was working on a product, in the banking industry, as a manager. Hence, I assumed that made me a Product Manager.\n>\n> I could not have been more wrong.\n>\n> When I talk to new PMs, the question I always hear is: \"What does a PM actually do?\"\n>\n> And it's not a simple answer — because the role varies widely across industries, company sizes, and stages.\n>\n> But here's what stays the same:\n>\n> PM is a people first job.\n>\n> It's about listening. Leading without authority. And making the hard calls when data and instinct conflict.\n>\n> Titles don't define you. Skills do. And the problems you've solved will always speak louder than the title on your resume.\n>\n> What was the real breakthrough moment that got you into product?\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This post contains nearly every signature Vik move in one compact piece — the contrarian opening (\"No one has a childhood dream...\"), the self-deprecating personal story, the one-line punch paragraph (\"I could not have been more wrong\"), the shift from story to extracted principle, the warm-but-direct advice, and the closing reader question. The voice is unmistakably his: specific, earned, conversational.\n\n---\n\n### Sample 2: \"111 Days\" — Humor + Self-Awareness (Personal)\n\n> Meet my most consistent habit this year. 111 days straight.\n>\n> No, not workouts.\n> Not journaling.\n>\n> It's LinkedIn!! 😂\n>\n> LinkedIn Games has quietly become one of my favorite daily rituals.\n>\n> Here's my quick take on each:\n>\n> 🧩 Pinpoint: Easily my favorite. Geography nerd mode activated.\n> 🔤 Queens: Still makes no sense to me without hints.\n> 🔀 Tango: Fun logic puzzle. Like a mini Sudoku with a twist.\n> 🏙️ Crossclimb: Solid. Perfect mix of trivia and strategy.\n>\n> The cherry on top? A friend of mine challenged me to a friendly competition. So now it's personal. 😆\n>\n> Who else here has quietly become a LinkedIn gamer? Which one is your jam?\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** Demonstrates Vik's humor voice — the staccato misdirection (\"No, not workouts. / Not journaling.\"), the genuine enthusiasm for something lighthearted, the \"cherry on top\" colloquialism, and the playful CTA. This is the fun, human Vik — no frameworks, no mentoring mode, just personality. The emoji usage is purposeful (😂, 😆) and the energy is high without being performative.\n\n---\n\n### Sample 3: \"Mentoring Reflections\" — Mission + Substance (Mentorship)\n\n> As the year wraps up, I was reflecting on all my conversations this year with folks I've been mentoring, and a few patterns stood out.\n>\n> Some of the biggest breakthroughs didn't come from frameworks or career hacks.\n>\n> They came from simple, often overlooked things:\n>\n> ✅ Asking for the promotion instead of waiting to be noticed.\n> ✅ Telling their story more clearly — not changing the resume, changing the narrative.\n> ✅ Realizing they were trying to change three variables at once (role + industry + location) and simplifying.\n> ✅ Pausing long enough to ask: \"Do I actually want this, or am I just running from something?\"\n>\n> Dozens landed new roles once they learned to tell their story more clearly. They had already put in the hard work — it just needed better storytelling.\n>\n> One person quit their MAG7 job the next day to start their own company. And is loving it.\n>\n> Another sent me an email years later saying our conversation during a tough job search \"had a profound impact on restoring my confidence.\"\n>\n> I can't tell you how gratifying that felt.\n>\n> Mentorship reminded me why I started in the first place. To help people move forward and see what's possible.\n>\n> If you're a PM looking for guidance, or if you just want to talk through where you are — I'm opening up a few mentorship spots for 2026.\n>\n> Comment 'AMA' if you want the invite.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This is Vik at his most substantive on LinkedIn — pattern recognition from real mentoring conversations, specific mentee outcomes (not vague claims), and genuine emotional disclosure (\"I can't tell you how gratifying that felt\") that connects to a mission statement. It shows the full post structure: reflective opener → pattern list → specific stories → personal meaning → CTA. The vulnerability is in service of a lesson, which is his consistent approach.\n\n---\n\n## Book Excerpts\n\n### Sample 4: \"How I Found My Dream Job\" — Career Narrative (Chapters 5–6)\n\n> Over 2 years, I went through 20,000+ job posts, applied to 4,000+ jobs, gave out over 1000 business cards, spoke with 250+ people on the phone for contacts and recommendations, and a 100+ interviews later, I finally got my dream job in the gaming industry!\n>\n> Me! I got two offers! Hallelujah!\n>\n> When I started at EA, I walked into their headquarters, and the first thing that hit me were the massive TV screens everywhere — showing gameplay trailers, upcoming titles. There were consoles set up in front of big chairs. Ginormous gaming statues lined the walkways.\n>\n> It felt like I was finally home.\n>\n> Here's what I learned from the entire process, and what I would tell anyone looking to break into a new industry:\n>\n> 1. **Don't apply for the role you want. Apply for what you know.** People hire you for what you know, not what you want to be. I applied for hundreds of PM jobs and heard nothing. The moment I started applying for analytics roles — my actual skillset — the calls started coming.\n>\n> 2. **It's a numbers game, but it's also a relationships game.** I was attending 8-10 meetup.com events a month. And more conferences, like Uncubed. Every person I met was a potential connection to a job that wasn't posted yet.\n>\n> 3. **Focus on what you enjoy. The job will come with time.** I could have given up after the first year. After the second round of rejections at Disney. After the Google realization. But I genuinely wanted to be in gaming, and that belief kept me going.\n>\n> And if you're wondering whether the grind was worth it — I had a character named after me in a game I worked on. A Ranged Mountain Titan Ape named Aga'Vik.\n>\n> That's it, quick and easy.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This captures the emotional arc that defines Vik's long-form voice — the quantified grind, the exclamation-mark joy of the payoff (\"Me! Hallelujah!\"), the sensory detail of walking into EA, the shift into numbered lessons, and the wry, warm closer about Aga'Vik. It demonstrates his rhythm: massive buildup sentence → short emotional burst → specific scene-setting → extracted principles → fun personal detail. The voice moves between vulnerability and confidence without sounding either self-pitying or bragging.\n\n---\n\n### Sample 5: \"Players Should Want to Pay\" — PM Philosophy (Chapter 4)\n\n> Players should \"want\" to pay and not \"have\" to pay. That's the golden rule.\n>\n> I've seen too many games where the monetization strategy was designed to squeeze every last dollar out of the player base. And the result was always the same: players churned, reviews tanked, and the studio spent three times as much trying to reacquire the players they'd already lost.\n>\n> It would have been easier and a lot cheaper to fix the bugs first.\n>\n> Let me give you an example. Marvel Snap is one of the best mobile games I've played since Clash Royale. When it launched, it didn't try to squeeze you for money. It kept gameplay fair, the progression felt meaningful, and the competitive experience was balanced.\n>\n> You know what happened? I was happy to pay. Voluntarily. Because the game was fun first.\n>\n> Compare that to games that put up paywalls early, lock content behind premium currency, and push aggressive pop-up offers every time you open the app. You might get a spike in revenue in Week 1. But by Week 4, half your players are gone. And now you're spending more on acquisition to replace the players you burned.\n>\n> What you're actually not doing is making more money. You're just getting the revenue in advance from future spend.\n>\n> The best monetization strategies are invisible. The player doesn't feel like they're being sold to. They feel like they're investing in an experience they enjoy. That's the difference between a game that has legs and a game that peaks and crashes.\n>\n> Don't be scared to make money. Just make sure the fun comes first.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This shows Vik's teaching voice at its most persuasive — a clear thesis stated upfront, followed by a negative example, then a positive example (Marvel Snap), then the counterargument dismantled with a single sharp line (\"What you're actually not doing is making more money\"), then the clean principle restatement. No jargon walls, no abstract pontificating — just specific products, specific behaviors, and a memorable closer. It demonstrates his ability to argue a strong position without sounding preachy.\n\n---\n\n### Sample 6: \"The Returning User Problem\" — Industry Critique (Chapter 4)\n\n> Here's something that drives me crazy as a gamer: RTUE, or Returning User Experience.\n>\n> I played Horizon Zero Dawn religiously when it came out. Got deep into the story, explored every corner of the map. Then life happened — I stopped playing for a few weeks.\n>\n> When I came back, I was stuck in a dungeon. I couldn't remember the controls. I couldn't figure out how to escape. There was no \"welcome back\" tutorial, no recap of what I'd been doing, no gentle re-onboarding.\n>\n> I quit. For good.\n>\n> Same thing happened with Diablo 4. I came back for Season 4, \"Loot Reborn,\" almost a year after launch. I had to watch hours of YouTube and ask strangers on Discord just to understand what had changed. I shouldn't have to watch 1-2 hours of YouTube videos to start replaying a game.\n>\n> And I work in this industry. I know how these games work. Imagine what a casual player goes through.\n>\n> RTUE is massively underinvested. Studios spend millions on acquiring new players and almost nothing on re-engaging the ones who already cared enough to download and play. It's one of the biggest blind spots in the industry.\n>\n> Every game should ask: what happens when a player comes back after 30 days? After 60? After a year? If the answer is \"they'll figure it out\" — you've already lost them.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This captures Vik's \"industry insider with a genuine complaint\" voice. He's not posturing or theorizing — he's telling you about a game he quit and why. The credibility line (\"And I work in this industry\") lands because it comes after the personal frustration, not before it. The structure is clean: personal story → second example reinforcing the pattern → zoomed-out industry critique → prescriptive reframe. The last line is quotable and actionable. This is Vik at his most passionate about a product opinion.\n\n---\n\n## Interview Excerpts\n\n### Sample 7: \"The Origin Story\" — Discovery Moment (Spoken)\n\n> So how did I wind up in gaming? Long story short, I was, uh, I was couch surfing at a friend's house and his roommate worked at a gaming company. And I remember I'm sitting there and I'm like — wait, gaming is a real job? You can get a job in games? People actually work in video games?\n>\n> That's a real job?!\n>\n> And I was like, I have to be in this industry. So I went home and I started applying. I was like, OK, I work on a product, I'm a manager, so I must be a product manager. Right?\n>\n> Apparently it doesn't work that way.\n>\n> I applied for, I don't know, dozens of companies. Nothing. Crickets. Not a single callback. And at that point I didn't really understand why. I thought, I have the experience, I've worked in banking, I've done consulting — why would they not want me?\n>\n> And it took someone at a conference — a guy named Greg — to tell me: \"Vik, you should apply for what you know, not what you want to do.\" And that was the moment. That was the turning point. I started applying for analytics roles instead of PM roles, and within weeks I'm getting calls from EA, Sony, Google.\n>\n> That advice made all the difference.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This is the raw spoken Vik — \"So\" as a launcher, \"I'm like\" for internal monologue, \"Right?\" as a checkpoint, \"Nothing. Crickets.\" for two-word impact. The self-deprecating humor (\"Apparently it doesn't work that way\") is perfectly timed. You can hear the energy shift when he hits the Greg moment — from casual frustration to something genuinely grateful. This excerpt shows how his spoken and written voices share DNA (the same story, the same punchlines) while the delivery is looser, more improvisational, more peppered with fillers that give it humanity.\n\n---\n\n### Sample 8: \"The Grind, Quantified\" — Perseverance Narrative (Spoken)\n\n> I looked at over 20,000 job positions. I applied for over 3,000 of them. I gave out — I bought four boxes of 250 business cards. I gave out 1,000 business cards. I spoke to about 200 people on the phone. I did roughly a hundred interviews.\n>\n> And this was over two years. Right?\n>\n> I was attending, I want to say, like 8 to 10 meetup.com events a month. And I'm an introvert. So walking up to a group of four people who are already talking, saying \"Hello\" — everyone looks at you — it's a little both embarrassing and hard to put yourself out there. But I did it. Because I really, really wanted this.\n>\n> I definitely hit the pavement and really grinded it out.\n>\n> And, you know, when people ask me about breaking into a new industry, I tell them — it's a numbers game. But it's also a relationship game. And you have to be willing to be uncomfortable. Because no one is going to hand it to you.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A GOOD CALIBRATION SAMPLE:** This is Vik at his most honest and distinctive — the numbers are his proof (not vague claims about \"working hard\"), the introvert-at-meetups detail is specific and vulnerable, and the doubled intensifier (\"really, really wanted this\") is pure signature. The shift from personal struggle to extracted principle (\"it's a numbers game, but it's also a relationship game\") shows how he teaches in conversation — story first, lesson second, always earned. The \"Right?\" after \"over two years\" is a perfect example of his spoken rhythm.\n";
